Title: Trek Rental Quality Bikes
text: Hello, We have three bikes here.  Two are Treks and the 3rd is a Diamondback.  the frame and wheel size listed are wrong.  One Trek is the largest they made and the other Trek is the smallest.  The Diamondback is what I'd call a bike for someone around 5' tall or so. The two Treks are rental quality.  We bought them to use everywhere and have zero issues.  If you aren't familiar with rental quality they are kinda bombproof.  They come with very tough frames and upgraded components plus things like tube liners and so forth.  We have loved these but we are headed in a different direction now. All three have a bit of rust.  All three will need a bit of attention.   The Treks were VERY expensive.  We bought them in Sonoma, California where we lived when we purchased them. The Diamondback is only $50. The Treks only have probably about 900,000 miles left. Thanks,

Title: Vans SE Bikes Lil Ripper
text: With over 40 years of production, the PK Ripper is the most famous and longest-running bike in the history of BMX. It honors a legacy both innovative and timeless. This year we collaborated with Vans, the original action sports footwear and apparel company, to produce the first-ever Vans PK Ripper, and we also made a limited-edition 16” version of the bike named the LiL’ Ripper. This means that even the youngsters have a chance to ride like the legends. The Vans LiL’ Ripper features details like a Vans checkerboard padset and Vans ‘66 valve caps.   Vans was founded in 1966 in Anaheim, CA, and the brand is embedded in BMX culture. Many top riders throughout the history of the sport including “PK” himself, Perry Kramer, have worn Vans shoes and ridden in many Vans-sponsored BMX races and events.  Key Features Vans edition 6061 aluminum LiL’ Ripper frame w/ Floval tubing and looptail rear end Limited edition & individually numbered on the inside of the rear dropout “Off the Wall” Landing Gear forks SE 3-pc 6061 alloy cranks SE Wing bars Vans x SE Bikes mini seat Vans Checkerboard Padset & ‘66 Dice valve caps included 20 pounds

Title: 2019 Santa Cruz Blur CC (Large)
text: FAST! FAST! FAST!  Original Owner - find me at the Sea Otter Classic in Monterey this week/weekend (April 6-10) to check it out in person.  Bought this bicycle new after a podium finish at Cactus Cup and absolutely LOVE the carbon weight and speed of it. I'll have to weigh it again, but I think it sinks the scale to a whopping 23 lbs... WITH PEDALS!  Shifter Lock Out Reserve Wheels (lifetime warranty) SRAM XO1 Eagle drivetrain  Strava says I've put 1,041.5 miles on the Blur. Aside from riding around to lube the grupo, cruising campsites, and just rolling with no strain, it should be pretty accurate. That's roughly 30 miles/month... next to nothing.  I added the Reserve Wheels and just bought new brake pads, new Ground Control Grid 2Bliss tires (lubed with Orange sealant), new silicone grips, and a new XO1 chain (all December 2021)... My mouth is watering just typing this stuff.  I'm not going to be racing much anymore, so I'm looking to move toward an all-mountain platform to ride with the girlfriend and buddies of my older generation. Not throwing in the towel yet, but I'm in my fifties now and have found reasons to pull back the speed a bit.  Thanks for checking out the bike. Please ask questions and I'll tell you all that I can.  The bike retailed at $9,400 new when I bought it. Current retail for the 2022 Blur CC X01 with Reserve wheels from Santa Cruz runs approximately $10,000.  Call/text Chad 858.9hundred.59hundred

text: Introducing the New 2022 Cyberbike Electric Mountain Bikes   Riders agree: Nothing comes close to Cyberbike's combination of performance, value, style, and quality. More mid-drive power than ever Awesome new color graphic display Easier to ride, lower standover frame, the lowest of any mid-drive eMTB New, structurally superior, mountain ready rear suspension linkage The best brakes in the business, even Quad-piston brakes on some models! Massive brake rotors up to 220mm 34mm gold tube forks on some models up to 140mm travel Wider range of models  A proper e-Mountain bike needs to be mid-drive and have full suspension, it's as simple as that. Until now, if you wanted an electric mountain bike to tackle rugged trails, your choices have been heavy, low-quality, fat tire, hub-motor beach bikes, or legacy brands charging $4000 or more for low-power eBikes without full suspension.   Whether your knees are tired or you just want to shred, there is simply no better choice for performance and value than Cyberbike. An American company with great customer support: Cyberbike, USA. Cyberbike eBikes come all with the quietest and most powerful motor in its class, with a long range (65 miles and more) battery, and powerful e-spec hydraulic disk brakes that will be there when you need them. A lightweight package with 500 watts of power, top-of-the-line battery range, and quality components, all for the price of an inexpensive yet stellar bike! You'll get so much more than other eBikes with the CyberBike, it's the real e-MTB experience for the adventurous rider. Performance, specs, and quality components throughout, and the best warranty in the industry, from an American company with experienced American mechanics on call for all your tech support needs.  54 volt/500 watt climbing power with 13Amp hour Li-Ion battery and only 52 lbs means you'll get power and tons of battery range. Title: Green World Bikes e-Trolley Pro Electric Bike
text: Green World Bikes e-Trolley Pro Electric Bike  A compact folding electric bike for increased power and range, and easier folding. This bike can be ridden fully powered, power-assist (pedal and motor together) or fully manual pedaling. Bike folds up quickly without tools and can be placed in trunk or backseat. Battery has been newly rebuilt to provide more power and longer riding time. 16 Inch Wheels. Removable, lockable battery (key included). Charger included. Comfortable ride thanks to 2.125" diameter tires, padded comfort saddle, padded grips and a suspension seat post. Great accessories including a derailleur bash guard, chain guide, front and rear fenders, integrated LED lights and an awesome kickstand that works even when folded. List price was $1,299 plus tax, and that was with a lower capacity battery. Rebuilding the battery normally costs $500, so the value of this bike is worth more than $1,500. Bike was seldom used due to location.
